; A loop with no recur runs once and exits — almost always a mistake. The compiler
; WARNS (non-fatal) at the loop call-site, via the $warn builtin.
(defn int main ()
  (loop ((int i 0))
    (printf "this never repeats\n"))
  (return 0))
;==EXPECTED-WARNING==
<stdin>:4:3: warning[macro]: loop has no recur — it runs once and exits; did you forget (recur ...)?
  (loop ((int i 0))
  ^
